[40:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And here\'s what it does. You would feed it a set of photos of a certain scene, and it would reconstruct a 3D scene or a video from that. It can create new views of a scene that aren\'t even in the'

[40:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'original images. So, for example, let\'s say you have these six photos of this room. These were taken at different angles and lighting conditions, but afterwards you can just plug it through'

[40:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this AI and it would stitch everything together and it uses what are called these compressed light field tokens that basically reduce the amount of data needed to store these 3D images and videos while keeping the quality high.'

[41:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And after processing all this data, you basically get this 3D scene or video like this. And here are some other examples of some reconstructed 3D'

[41:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scenes. Now, here are some comparisons with other 3D scene generators. So, this other one is called LVSMED, and this video is around 9 MGB. Now, if you use'

[41:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this Clif one, it can output various different sizes. But notice that for the ones that are below 9 megabytes, the quality is just as good as this one. So, it\'s really good at compression and'

[41:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'creating an optimized 3D scene. Or here\'s a comparison with another one called depth splat. This is 14 megabytes in size. But you can see the details of almost everything in these scenes are'

[41:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pretty awful. Whereas for this one, even for the 11 megabyte version, the details are just a lot better and sharper. And then here are some more 3D reconstructions from Clif for your'

[42:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reference. Notice that for the most part, everything is very detailed and sharp, including the text. So, really quickly, if you\'re curious about the technical details, Clif uses a three-stage process. First, it tokenizes'

[42:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the image, or basically it converts it into data for the AI model to process. Then, it clusters these tokens and it removes any redundant tokens so that it can process this faster. And then'

[42:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finally, it compresses these tokens into what are called light field tokens, which are then used to generate new views of the scene. Now, if you scroll up to the top of the page, they have released a GitHub repo here. They say'

[42:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the code will be released around August 1st. Anyways, if you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Next up, this AI is really useful. It\'s called movies. And this can take a video and'

[42:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically reconstruct a 3D scene from it or what they call a 4D scene because the fourth dimension is time. And from that video, it can detect a ton of different things. For example, on the left is the'

[43:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'original video. And basically, if you feed it through this AI, it can capture everything in this 3D space, including the motion of the camera. So, if you get it to reconstruct the scene, here\'s what'

[43:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it looks like. And notice that it\'s almost the same as the original video. Now, because it can detect everything in this 3D space, including the position of the camera, you can get the camera to stay still. So, this is called fixed'

[43:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'novel viewpoint. And if you do that, here is what you get. So, notice that this can act as like a video stabilization tool. In addition to this, you can also predict the depth of the original video like this. Or you can'

[43:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'even predict the motion. In other words, what areas in this scene move over time? So the areas that are darker in color indicate higher movement. So as you can see, for example, his feet move a lot'

[44:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more than the rest of his body, and that\'s why his feet are darker colored. Or here are two other examples where on the left is the input video. Well, you can get this AI to reconstruct the scene, and it looks almost the same as'

[44:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the original video. Now, again, both input videos are super shaky. So, if you get the camera to be fixed at one position in time, here is what you get. And notice that it\'s really good at'

[44:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stabilizing the video and then you can also get it to predict the depth of the video as well as predict the motion of the video. In other words, what parts move the most in the video. And there\'s even more you can do with this. So, here'

[44:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are some additional examples. You can also get it to track certain parts of the video as they move. And you know, the spatial tracking is pretty good. As you can see from the scene at the top, even though it\'s moving very fast, it\'s'

[44:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'able to track this car very well. Or as you can see from the bottom, even though the camera is super shaky and also moving really quickly, it\'s able to track everything in the scene with pretty high accuracy. And you can also'

[45:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use this to segment different objects in the video. So, for example, let\'s say the input video is on the left. Well, you can get it to segment certain things in the video, like this car or this'

[45:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mecha dragon creature at the bottom. Here are some other examples. And notice on the bottom row, even though this is a super busy scene, it\'s able to track the movements of your targets very well.'

[45:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Really quickly, here\'s how it works. So it would take each frame from your video and plug this through an image encoder which would break the frame down into data and then feed it through this neural network to be processed. And then'

[45:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it goes through three different attention heads. One to detect the depth or geometry of the scene, another one to basically detect the appearance of the scene and the third one detects the motion of the scene. And so afterwards'

[45:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can get it to basically predict all these three different things. Now, if you scroll up to the top of the page, they have released a GitHub repo, and right now they haven\'t released any code yet, but it is on their to-do list.'

[46:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hopefully, they will release this soon because this is a super useful tool, especially if you need to segment, detect, or track things in videos. Anyways, if you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in'

